\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Asset Support Classification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All IT assets and systems operating within or connected to the Elko County network shall be assigned one of the following three support classifications.
 This classification is the authoritative basis for determining support ownership,
 work order routing,
 and service level obligations as defined in Policy 3.01 and throughout Chapter 3 of this manual.
 The IT Director shall ensure that each asset's support classification is recorded in the CMDB and maintained current as contracts,
 procurement arrangements,
 and operational responsibilities change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
IT-Managed
\series default
:
 Assets and systems that are wholly procured,
 configured,
 maintained,
 and supported by the Information Operations Department for the full duration of the asset's operational lifespan.
 The IT Department retains exclusive authority over all technical work performed on IT-Managed assets;
 no vendor,
 contractor,
 or department personnel shall perform technical work on these assets without explicit written authorization from the IT Director.
 All requests for service shall be submitted through the work order system.
 Examples include end-user computers,
 servers,
 network infrastructure,
 and any other technology that the IT Department has accepted full responsibility for.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
IT-Supported
\series default
:
 Assets and systems that are supported under a vendor contract or lease agreement,
 but for which the Information Operations Department provides first-line support for minor issues,
 with the option to escalate to the vendor when issues exceed local resolution capability or when the nature of the contract directs vendor involvement.
 The IT Department shall be the first point of contact for service requests on IT-Supported assets;
 however,
 direct contact with the vendor is permissible when the contract explicitly provides for it or when the issue is clearly outside the IT Department's scope of support.
 All service activity,
 whether performed by IT staff or escalated to the vendor,
 shall be documented in the work order system.
 Examples include court recording systems,
 public safety software applications,
 multifunction copiers under maintenance contracts,
 and similar systems under third-party agreements that permit local support participation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Vendor-Managed:

\series default
 Assets and systems for which the vendor retains exclusive support responsibility and over which the Information Operations Department exercises no technical authority.
 IT Department personnel shall not perform any technical work on Vendor-Managed systems beyond the minimum required to provide vendor access,
 such as assigning network addresses or granting physical facility access.
 All service requests for Vendor-Managed assets shall be referred directly to the vendor.
 The IT Department's responsibility is limited to facilitating vendor access and documenting any coordination activity in the work order system for tracking purposes.
 Examples include hosted government platform services and systems installed and maintained under exclusive vendor agreements with no local support provision.
\end_layout

